<TEI.2><TEIHEADER><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><TITLE TYPE="245">The Harley lyrics [a machine-readable transcription]</TITLE><AUTHOR>anonymous</AUTHOR><EDITOR ROLE="editor">Frances McSparran</EDITOR></TITLESTMT><EXTENT>ca. 750 kilobytes</EXTENT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><DISTRIBUTOR>University of Michigan, Humanities Text Initiative</DISTRIBUTOR><IDNO>HarLyr</IDNO><AVAILABILITY><P>Available at URL http://www.hti.umich.edu/english/mideng/</P><P>This text has been made available through the Oxford Text Archive for personal scholarly use only.  OTA number:  U-1681-A</P></AVAILABILITY><DATE>1993</DATE></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC><P>The electronic text was created from new transcriptions of the lyrics from the EETS facsimile of Harley 2253.  The transcriptions were made by students at the University of Michigan under the direction of Frances McSparran, and were corrected by Meredith Jones. Since they are new transcriptions, they may not match Brook's edition (see below) in all respects.  Words joined in the MS ("itelle") have been separated by a colon ("i:telle"). </P><P>The lyrics have been numbered and paginated to conform to Brook's printed edition by the University of Virginia Electronic Text Center. References are by lyric number (as in Brook), followed by line number.</P><BIBL><TITLE>Facsimile of British Museum MS. Harley 2253</TITLE><RESPSTMT><NAME>N. R. (Neil Ripley) Ker</NAME><RESP>With an introduction by</RESP></RESPSTMT><EXTENT>xxiii, [194] p. 32 cm.</EXTENT><PUBLISHER>Published for the Early English Text Society by Oxford University Press</PUBLISHER><PUBPLACE>London and New York</PUBPLACE><DATE>1965</DATE><TITLE TYPE="series">Early English Text Society (Series). Original series ; 255</TITLE></BIBL><BIBL><TITLE>The Harley lyrics : the Middle English lyrics of MS Harley 2253</TITLE><EDITOR ROLE="editor">G. L. Brook</EDITOR><EXTENT>x, 125 p. : facsims. ; 25 cm.</EXTENT><PUBLISHER>Manchester University Press</PUBLISHER><PUBPLACE>Manchester, Eng.</PUBPLACE><DATE>1948</DATE><TITLE TYPE="series">Publications of the University of Manchester, English  series, no. 302</TITLE></BIBL></SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><PROFILEDESC><CREATION><DATE>c. 1310</DATE></CREATION></PROFILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><CHANGE><DATE>February 9, 1994</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>Edward Gaynor</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library, Cataloging Services Dept.</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>TEI header completed</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>January 1994</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>David Seaman</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Electronic Text Center</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>Brought the tagging into line with the OTA.DTD, and parsed</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>November 1993</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>Kelly Tetterton</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Electronic Text Center</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>paginated to G.L. Brook's edition of The Harley lyrics (Manchester : Manchester University Press, 1948); the poems have been renumbered to match those of Brook's edition; note that because only English lyrics were transcribed, lyric #19 is not included.</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>June 1993</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>Peter J. Kastor</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Electronic Text Center</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>TEI SGML tagging added; UVA header added</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>1990 or 1991</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>John Price-Wilkin</NAME><RESP>University of Michigan</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>SGML tagging added</ITEM></CHANGE></REVISIONDESC></TEIHEADER><TEXT><BODY><DIV1 ID="K24B" N="1" TYPE="lyric"><HEAD>Brook 1; Ker 24b</HEAD><PB N="29"><L N="001">Er&thorn;e toc of er&thorn;e er&thorn;e wy&thorn; woh  </L><L N="002">Er&thorn;e o&thorn;er er&thorn;e to &thorn;e er&thorn;e droh  </L><L N="003">Er&thorn;e leyde er&thorn;e in er&thorn;ene &thorn;roh  </L><L N="004">&thorn;o heuede er&thorn;e of er&thorn;e er&thorn;e ynoh  </L></DIV1><DIV1 ID="K27" N="2" TYPE="lyric"><HEAD>Brook 2; Ker 27</HEAD><L N="001">Middelerd for mon wes mad  </L><L N="002">vnmihti aren is meste mede  </L><L N="003">&thorn;is hedy ha&thorn; on honde yhad  </L><L N="004">&thorn;at heuene hem is hest to hede  </L><L N="005">Icherde a blisse budel vs bad  </L><L N="006">&thorn;e dreri domesdai to drede  </L><L N="007">of sunful sauhting sone be sad  </L><L N="008">&thorn;at derne do&thorn; &thorn;is derne dede  </L><L N="009">&thorn;ah he ben derne done  </L><L N="010">&thorn;is wrakeful werkes vnder wede  </L><L N="011">in soule sotele&thorn; sone  </L><L N="012">sone is sotel as ich ou sai  </L><L N="013">&thorn;is sake al&thorn;ah hit seme suete  </L><L N="014">&thorn;at i:telle a poure play  </L><L N="015">&thorn;at furst is feir &amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e vnsete  </L><L N="016">&thorn;is wilde wille went awai  </L><L N="017">wi&thorn; mone &amp; mournyng muchel vnmete   <PB N="30"> </L><L N="018">&thorn;at liue&thorn; on likyng out of lay  </L><L N="019">his hap he de&thorn; ful harde on hete  </L><L N="020">a&yogh;eyn&yogh; he howe&thorn; henne  </L><L N="021">alle is &thorn;riuene &thorn;ewes &thorn;rete  </L><L N="022">&thorn;at &thorn;enke&thorn; nout on &thorn;enne  </L><L N="023">a&yogh;eynes &thorn;enne vs &thorn;rete&thorn; &thorn;re  </L><L N="024">&yogh;ef he be&thorn; &thorn;ryuen &amp; &thorn;owen in &thorn;eode  </L><L N="025">vr soule bonc so broerli be  </L><L N="026">as berne best &thorn;at bale forbeode  </L><L N="027">&thorn;at wole wihtstonden streyn&thorn;e of &thorn;eo  </L><L N="028">is rest is reued wi&thorn; &thorn;e reode  </L><L N="029">fyth of o&thorn;er ne dar&thorn; he floc  </L><L N="030">&thorn;at fleishshes faunyng furst foreode  </L><L N="031">&thorn;at falsist is of fyue  </L><L N="032">&yogh;ef we leue&thorn; eny leode  </L><L N="033">werryng is worst of wyue  </L><L N="034">wyues wille were ded wo  </L><L N="035">&yogh;ef he is wicked forte welde  </L><L N="036">&thorn;at burst shal bete for hem bo  </L><L N="037">he shal him burewen &thorn;ah he hire belde  </L><L N="038">by body ant soule y:sugge al so  </L><L N="039">&thorn;at some beo&thorn; founden vnder felde  </L><L N="040">&thorn;at ha&thorn; to fere is meste fo  </L><L N="041">of gomenes he mai gon al gelde  </L><L N="042">ant sore ben fered on folde  </L><L N="043">lest he to harmes helde  </L><L N="044">ant happes hente vnholde  </L><L N="045">hom vnholdest her is on  </L><L N="046">wi&thorn;outen helle ase ich hit holde  </L><L N="047">so fele bue&thorn; founden monnes fon  </L><L N="048">&thorn;e furst of hem biforen ytolde  </L><L N="049">&thorn;er afterward &thorn;is worldes won  </L><L N="050">wi&thorn; muchel vnwynne vs woren wolde  </L><L N="051">sone be&thorn; &thorn;is gomenes gon  </L><L N="052">&thorn;at make&thorn; vs so brag &amp; bolde  </L><L N="053">ant bidde&thorn; vs ben bly&thorn;e  </L><L N="054">an ende he caste&thorn; ous fol colde  </L><L N="055">in sunne &amp; serewe sy&thorn;e   <PB N="31"> </L><L N="056">In sunne &amp; sorewe y am seint  </L><L N="057">&thorn;at siwe&thorn; me sosully sore  </L><L N="058">my mur&thorn;e is al wi&thorn; mournyng meind  </L><L N="059">ne may ich my&thorn;en hit namore  </L><L N="060">when we be&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;is world forwleynt  </L><L N="061">&thorn;at we ne lustne&thorn; lyues lore  </L><L N="062">&thorn;e fend in fyht vs fynt so feynt  </L><L N="063">we falle&thorn; so flour when hit is frore  </L><L N="064">for folkes fader al fleme  </L><L N="065">Wo him wes ywarpe &yogh;ore  </L><L N="066">&thorn;at Crist nul nowyht queme  </L><L N="067">To queme crist we weren ycore  </L><L N="068">ant kend ys craftes forte knowe  </L><L N="069">Leue we nout we buen forlore  </L><L N="070">in lustes &thorn;ah we lyggen lowe  </L><L N="071">We shule aryse vr fader byfore  </L><L N="072">&thorn;ah fon vs fallen vmbe &thorn;rowe  </L><L N="073">to borewen vs alle he wes ybore  </L><L N="074">&thorn;is bonnyng when him bemes blowe  </L><L N="075">he byt vs buen of hyse  </L><L N="076">ant on ys ryhthond hente rowe  </L><L N="077">Wy&thorn; ryht wysemen to aryse  </L></DIV1><DIV1 ID="K28" N="3" TYPE="lyric"><HEAD>Brook 3; Ker 28</HEAD><L N="001">Ichot a burde in a bour ase beryl so bryht  </L><L N="002">ase saphyr in seluer semly on syht  </L><L N="003">ase iaspe &thorn;e gentil &thorn;at leme&thorn; wi&thorn; lyht  </L><L N="004">ase gernet in golde &amp; ruby wel ryht  </L><L N="005">ase onycle he ys on yholden on hyht  </L><L N="006">ase diamaund &thorn;e dere in day when he is dyht  </L><L N="007">he is coral ycud wi&thorn; cayser ant knyht  </L><L N="008">ase emeraude amorewen &thorn;is may haue&thorn; myht  </L><L N="009">&thorn;e myht of &thorn;e margarite haue&thorn; &thorn;is mai mere  </L><L N="010">For charbocle ich hire chos bi chyn &amp; by chere  </L><L N="011">hire rode is ase rose &thorn;at red is on rys  </L><L N="012">wi&thorn; lilye white leres lossum he is  </L><L N="013">&thorn;e primerole he passe&thorn; paruenke of pris  </L><L N="014">wi&thorn; alisaundre &thorn;areto ache &amp; anys  </L><L N="015">coynte ase columbine such hire cunde ys  </L><L N="016">glad vnder gore in gro &amp; in grys   <PB N="32"> </L><L N="017">he is blosme opon bleo brihtest vnder bis  </L><L N="018">wi&thorn; celydoyne ant sauge ase &thorn;ou &thorn;iself sys  </L><L N="019">&thorn;at syht vpon &thorn;at semly to blis he is broht  </L><L N="020">he is solsecle to sauue ys forsoht  </L><L N="021">he is papeiai in pyn &thorn;at bete&thorn; me my bale  </L><L N="022">to trewe tortle in a tour y telle &thorn;e mi tale  </L><L N="023">he is &thorn;rustle &thorn;ryuen in &thorn;ro &thorn;at singe&thorn; in sale  </L><L N="024">&thorn;e wilde laueroc ant wolc &amp; &thorn;e wodewale  </L><L N="025">he is faucoun in friht dernest in dale  </L><L N="026">ant wi&thorn; eueruch a gome gladest in gale  </L><L N="027">From weye he is wisist in to wyrhale  </L><L N="028">hire nome is  in a:note of &thorn;e nyhtegale  </L><L N="029">In annote is hire nome nempne&thorn; hit non  </L><L N="030">whose ryht rede&thorn; roune to Johon.  </L><L N="031">muge he is ant mondrake &thorn;ouh miht of &thorn;e mone  </L><L N="032">trewe triacle ytold wi&thorn; tonges in trone  </L><L N="033">such licoris mai leche from lyne to lone  </L><L N="034">such sucre mon seche&thorn; &thorn;at saue&thorn; men sone  </L><L N="035">bli&thorn;e yblessed of crist &thorn;at  baye&thorn; me mi bone  </L><L N="036">when derne dede is in dayne derne are done  </L><L N="037">ase g»oºmyl in g»eºue grene is &thorn;e grone  </L><L N="038">ase quibibe &amp; comyn cud is in crone  </L><L N="039">Cud comyn in court canel in cofre  </L><L N="040">wi&thorn; gyngyure &amp; sedewale &amp; &thorn;e gylofre  </L><L N="041">he is medierne of miht mercie of mede  </L><L N="042">Rekene ase regnas resoun to rede  </L><L N="043">Trewe ase tegeu in tour ase wyrwein in wede  </L><L N="044">baldore &thorn;en byrne &thorn;at of &thorn;e bor bede  </L><L N="045">Ase Wylcadoun he is wys dohty of dede  </L><L N="046">Feyrore &thorn;en floyres folkes to fede  </L><L N="047">Cud ase cradoc in court carf &thorn;e brede  </L><L N="048">hendore &thorn;en hilde &thorn;at haue&thorn; me to hede  </L><L N="049">he haue&thorn; me to hede &thorn;is hendy anon  </L><L N="050">gentil ase ionas heo ioye&thorn; wi&thorn; Ion  </L></DIV1><PB N="33"><DIV1 ID="K29" N="4" TYPE="lyric"><HEAD>Brook 4; Ker 29</HEAD><L N="001">Bytuene mersh &amp; aueril.  </L><L N="002">when spray biginne&thorn; to springe  </L><L N="003">&thorn;e lutel foul ha&thorn; hire wyl  </L><L N="004">on hyre lud to synge  </L><L N="005">Ich libbe in louelonginge  </L><L N="006">for semlokest of alle &thorn;ynge.  </L><L N="007">he may me blisse bringe  </L><L N="008">icham in hire baundoun  </L><L N="009">An hendy hap ichabbe yhent  </L><L N="010">ichot from heuene it is me sent  </L><L N="011">from alle wymmen mi loue is lent  </L><L N="012">&amp; lyht on alysoun  </L><L N="013">on heu hire her is fayr ynoh  </L><L N="014">hire browe broune hire e&yogh;e blake  </L><L N="015">wi&thorn; lossum chere he on me loh  </L><L N="016">wi&thorn; middel smal &amp; wel ymake  </L><L N="017">bote he me wolle to hire take  </L><L N="018">forte buen hire owen make  </L><L N="019">longe to lyuen ichulle forsake  </L><L N="020">&amp; feye fallen adoun  </L><L N="021">an hendy hap  &amp;c  </L><L N="022">nihtes when y wende &amp; wake  </L><L N="023">for&thorn;i myn wonges waxe&thorn; won.  </L><L N="024">leuedi al for &thorn;ine sake  </L><L N="025">longinge is ylent me on.  </L><L N="026">In world nis non so wytermon.  </L><L N="027">&thorn;at al hire bounte telle con  </L><L N="028">hire swyre is whittore &thorn;en &thorn;e swon  </L><L N="029">&amp; feyrest may in toune  </L><L N="030">An hend &amp;c  </L><L N="031">Icham for wolwyng al forwake  </L><L N="032">wery so water in wore  </L><L N="033">lest eny reue me my make  </L><L N="034">ychabbe y&yogh;yrned &yogh;ore  </L><L N="035">Betere is &thorn;olien whyle sore  </L><L N="036">&thorn;en mournen euermore  </L><L N="037">geynest vnder gore  </L><L N="038">herkne to me roun.  </L><L N="039">An hendi &amp;c  </L></DIV1><PB N="34"><DIV1 ID="K30" N="5" TYPE="lyric"><HEAD>Brook 5; Ker 30</HEAD><L N="001">Wi&thorn; longyng y am lad  </L><L N="002">on molde y waxe mad  </L><L N="003"> a maide marre&thorn; me  </L><L N="004">y:grede y:grone vnglad  </L><L N="005">for selden y am sad  </L><L N="006">&thorn;at semly forte se  </L><L N="007">leuedi &thorn;ou rewe me  </L><L N="008">to rou&thorn;e &thorn;ou hauest me rad  </L><L N="009">be bote  of &thorn;at y bad  </L><L N="010">my lyf is long on &thorn;e  </L><L N="011">leuedy of alle londe  </L><L N="012">les me out of bonde  </L><L N="013">broht icham in wo  </L><L N="014">haue:resting on honde  </L><L N="015">&amp; sent &thorn;ou me &thorn;i sonde  </L><L N="016">sone er &thorn;ou me slo  </L><L N="017">my reste is wi&thorn; &thorn;e ro  </L><L N="018">&thorn;ah men to me han onde  </L><L N="019">to loue nuly noht wonde  </L><L N="020">ne lete for:non of &thorn;o  </L><L N="021">leuedi wi&thorn; al my miht  </L><L N